        <!-- The Hook -->
                <div class="bg-brandBlue/5 border-l-4 border-brandOrange p-6 rounded-r-xl mb-6">
                    <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 italic">The definitive guide to importing chargers from China. Learn about Incoterms, freight options, shipping costs, customs clearance, and how to <a href="/blog/import-costs-guide" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange font-semibold">calculate total landed costs</a>.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">According to the <a href="https://fbx.freightos.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange underline">Freightos Baltic Index (FBX)</a>, shipping a 40-foot container from China to the US West Coast averaged $1,500-3,000 in 2025, with rates fluctuating based on demand, fuel costs, and port congestion.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">According to the <a href="https://www.usitc.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange underline">US International Trade Commission (USITC)</a>, Section 301 tariffs on Chinese electronics range from 7.5% to 25%, making customs classification and duty planning essential components of any importing strategy.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">2026 freight reality is shaped by two regulatory shocks. First, the <strong>$800 Section 321 de minimis</strong> exemption ended for China and Hong Kong origin on <strong>May 2, 2025</strong>, and was suspended for all origins on <strong>August 29, 2025</strong>. Every parcel now pays full duty or a $200 flat postal duty, making DDP the default for predictable landed cost. Second, the <strong>IATA DGR 67th Edition</strong> and <strong>IMDG Code 42-24</strong> require <strong>state of charge (SOC) of 30 percent or less</strong> for UN3481 lithium battery shipments from <strong>January 1, 2026</strong>, with valid UN38.3 test reports mandatory for every power bank.</p>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">Spot rates have settled rather than spiked. China to US West Coast averages <strong>$2,000-2,800 per 20GP</strong> and <strong>$2,650-4,100 per 40HC</strong> to the East Coast. Air freight to the US sits around <strong>$7.00 per kg</strong> (up 20 percent year on year), while China to Europe air has surged to roughly <strong>$4.80 per kg</strong> (up about 75 percent year on year). China-Europe rail freight remains a useful middle ground at <strong>$1.80-2.60 per kg</strong> with 22-28 day transit. Express courier (DHL, FedEx, UPS) runs <strong>$8-15 per kg</strong> door to door.</p>
                </div>

