                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">5. Customs Clearance Process</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">Customs clearance is often the most confusing part of importing. Understanding the process helps avoid delays and unexpected costs.</p>

                    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-xl p-6 mb-6">
                        <h4 class="font-black text-amber-700 uppercase mb-2">2026 Lithium Battery Shipping Update</h4>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3">Power banks and devices with built-in lithium batteries (UN3481, over 2.7 Wh) face stricter shipping rules effective January 1, 2026. The <strong>IATA DGR 67th Edition</strong> and <strong>IMDG Code 42-24</strong> now require:</p>
                        <ul class="text-slate-600 text-sm space-y-1 ml-4 list-disc">
                            <li><strong>SOC ≤30%</strong> (state of charge) for both air and sea shipments. Special Provision A331 is the only exception path and requires written approval from both the State of Origin and the State of the Operator.</li>
                            <li>Valid <strong>UN38.3 test report</strong> from a CNAS or CMA accredited lab.</li>
                            <li>MSDS must explicitly state SOC ≤30% compliance.</li>
                            <li>SOC compliance statement on the shipping documents to avoid airport security rejection.</li>
                            <li>Lithium battery mark (100×100 mm) on every outer carton.</li>
                            <li><strong>EU Battery Regulation 2023/1542:</strong> the EU Battery Passport becomes mandatory on February 18, 2027, but the scope covers EV batteries, light-means-of-transport batteries, and industrial batteries above 2 kWh. Consumer power banks are not in the 2027 scope, although early Digital Product Passport adoption is encouraged.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs mt-3">WOWOHCOOL pre-discharges every power bank to under 30% SOC, issues a SOC compliance statement, and provides UN38.3 test reports plus the lithium battery mark on every export carton.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6">
                            <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-4">Required Documentation</h3>
                            <ul class="text-slate-600 text-sm space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
                                <li><strong>Commercial Invoice:</strong> detailed invoice with HS codes, values, and the Incoterm in effect.</li>
                                <li><strong>Packing List:</strong> contents, quantities, weights, and carton dimensions.</li>
                                <li><strong>Bill of Lading (B/L) or Air Waybill (AWB):</strong> ocean bill for sea freight, AWB for air.</li>
                                <li><strong>Certificate of Origin:</strong> required for preferential tariffs (FTA countries) and to evidence China origin for Section 301 calculation.</li>
                                <li><strong>Product Specifications:</strong> technical details for HS code classification.</li>
                                <li><strong>FCC SDoC / FDA Registration:</strong> required for radio-frequency electronics and certain medical-adjacent devices entering the US.</li>
                                <li><strong>UN38.3 Test Report and SOC Compliance Statement:</strong> mandatory for any shipment containing lithium batteries.</li>
                            </ul>
